03782nam a22006015i 9780674271630DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222009mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742716307 a10.4159/97806742716302doi  a(DE-B1597)613851  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aLB775.F82bC73 2009eb 7aSOC0530002bisacsh04a370.922231 aCraig, Albert M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCivilization and Enlightenment :bThe Early Thought of Fukuzawa Yukichi /cAlbert M. Craig. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (212 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Scottish Enlightenment and the Stages of Civilization -- t2 American Geography Textbooks -- t3 John Hill Burton’s Political Economy -- t4 Invention, the Engine of Progress -- t5 An Outline of Theories of Civilization -- tReflections -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Sources and Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea that society progresses through stages of development, from savagery to civilization, arose in eighteenth-century Europe. Albert Craig traces how Fukuzawa Yukichi, deeply influenced by the Scottish Enlightenment, “translated” the idea for Japanese society, both enriching and challenging the concept. Fukuzawa, an official in the Tokugawa government, saw his career collapse when the shogunate ended in 1867. Reinventing himself as a thinker and writer, he made his life work the translation and interpretation of the Western idea of the stages of civilization. He interpreted key Scottish intellectuals— Adam Smith, Adam Ferguson, William Robertson, John Millar; relied on American geographies to help explain how societies progress; and focused on invention as a key to civilization. By defining the role of “less developed” nations in the world order, Fukuzawa added a new dimension to the stage theory. But by the end of the 1880s, he had come to dismiss the philosophy of natural rights as “the fatuous idealism of Christian ministers.” Though civilization—as represented by Britain—was still his goal for Japan, he no longer saw the West as a uniformly beneficial moral force. This engaging history offers an illuminating look at an important figure and the world of ideas in nineteenth-century Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Regional Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674271630zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674271630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674271630/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK